The paper deals with a geometric problem of finding shortest paths in a polygonal domain, which is a typical topic in computational geometry (cs.CG). The authors also use Davenport-Schinzel sequences, which are a well-known tool in computational geometry and combinatorics (cs.DS). The paper involves analyzing the complexity of the problem and providing a tradeoff between space and query time, which are typical topics in algorithms and data structures (cs.DM). The authors also mention the case where query points should lie on a given set of line segments, which is related to computational geometry and graph theory (cs.CC, cs.GR).
